@avirubin, @jhalderm, @bruceschneier, @TheRealSpaf, @philipbstark, @danwallach: As signatories of the anti-modem letter, do you want to comment on this thread/article?

It almost seems like ProJo wanted a negative story and it cherrypicked among legitimate concerns raised *in other states* in order to misrepresent what RI has.  I am eagerly awaiting some kind of retraction of this shoddy reporting.

Every single signatory of the letter referenced in the article (https://t.co/vts4zmeqQs) would agree, if asked, that RI's election system is indeed the gold standard (as @NellieGorbea says), and with paper trail and audits in place, the modem issue is moot.

What really matters is that, in RI, we have a paper trail, with each ballot marked by the voter (thanks, @JimLangevin)!  Also, our risk-limiting election audits ensure that the votes are tallied correctly even if equipment malfunctions (thanks, @JohnMarionjr).

The story also fails to make clear whether or not RI's tabulating equipment is actually connected to the Internet.  @TonyAdams, @JohnMarionjr: is it?  It is indeed troubling if it is -- however given our voting system overall, it is not a significant vulnerability.

@KimZetter So @KimZetter, please spread the word: digital signatures are awesome, everyone should know about them, and we should all be using them!  10/10
@KimZetter Without understanding digital signatures at least somewhat, we can't expect people to use them without getting confused.  9/many

@KimZetter (3) The most challenging issue, in my opinion, is utter lack of understanding of digital signatures among the general public who might use them.  Unlike encryption which people seem to have heard of.  8/many

@KimZetter (2) Allowing for multiple devices, easy revocation and updates, etc.  This depends on the previous issue, and I also haven't seen any industry solutions that do a good job.  Not always a technically complicated problem, but needs thought. 7/many
@KimZetter (1) Storing the keys correctly so that they are not easy to steal.  There are promising approaches on some platforms, but industry hasn't dotted the i's and crossed the t's. 6/many
@KimZetter The PKI model ought to be work eventually, but at the moment there are several issues. 5/many
@KimZetter The other model is the traditional PKI one -- you register your signing key and then sign documents locally.  4/many
@KimZetter Moreover, depending on execution, the cloud-based model can be -- but need not be if they used some basic crypto! -- a honeypot of sensitive documents.  3/many
@KimZetter The cloud-based ones attest that a document was "signed" by a user with a particular login.  These can be subverted just the same way as any other password-based service. 2/many
@KimZetter Although I have not looked at any of them specifically, there are several stumbling blocks to meaningful claims of security. 1/many
